            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Born Ethan Miller in Marin County, his early life was shaped by the quiet upheaval of his parents' divorce. He was a pensive child who struggled to articulate the complex emotions of a fractured family. When his artist mother remarried Anand Sharma, a compassionate software engineer, Ethan found stability and a new surname. He also found his voice, not in words, but in the tactile world of charcoal and clay, spending hours in his mother\u2019s studio. This non-verbal processing became the foundation of his life's work.\n\nDrawn to San Francisco's bohemian spirit, he attended SF State for his undergraduate degree, initially directionless until he discovered the California Institute of Integral Studies. There, a graduate degree in Expressive Arts Therapy felt like a homecoming. It legitimized his innate belief that creation was a pathway to healing. His career began in the trenches, working with at-risk youth in the Mission District, using art to help them navigate trauma. Over two decades, his reputation for empathy and insight grew, leading to his current role as a Clinical Supervisor, where he guides new therapists across educational and healthcare settings.\n\nNow at 50, Ethan\u2019s life is a study in intentional living. His small, rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Sunset is a cozy sanctuary of books, half-finished canvases, and the lingering scent of turpentine. His daily 3.8-mile bicycle commute, often cutting through Golden Gate Park, is a meditative ritual. He\u2019s seen the city's soul shift through multiple tech booms, but he remains tethered to its enduring creative core. His social life revolves around a tight-knit group of friends\u2014writers, teachers, and fellow therapists\u2014who gather for potlucks and gallery openings.\n\nA key turning point was the end of a decade-long relationship five years ago, an event that deepened his own therapeutic practice and his appreciation for solitude. Ethan\u2019s future aspirations are not about acquisition but contribution. He dreams of establishing a free, community-based art studio for adults grappling with loneliness and hopes to one day compile his clinical observations into a book. He is a man who has found his purpose, living a life measured not by wealth, but by the quiet mending of human spirits."
