        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being ten, his small hands covered in cold, grey clay in his mother's studio. He wasn't sculpting anything; he was just pummeling the lump, gouging it with his thumbs, feeling the knot of his parents' split loosen in his own chest with each impact. His mother watched silently from the doorway, not with pity, but with a quiet understanding. In that moment, without a single word, he learned that creating something\u2014even a formless mess\u2014could be a form of release, a way to speak when you had no words.\n\n2.\nAt fourteen, standing with his mother and Anand at the DMV to get his new ID card, the clerk called \u201cEthan Sharma.\u201d The name felt foreign and solid in his mouth. It was the first time he had chosen a piece of his own identity. Saying it aloud was like laying down a foundation stone for a new life, one built not on the rubble of what was lost, but on the quiet strength of the man who chose to be his father. It was the beginning of true stability.\n\n3.\nHe was an aimless SF State student until he saw a course catalog for the California Institute of Integral Studies. He recalls standing under the fluorescent lights of the campus library, his finger tracing the words \u201cExpressive Arts Therapy.\u201d A profound sense of recognition washed over him. It wasn\u2019t just a degree program; it was a name for what he had always known instinctively in his mother's studio. It was the moment his life\u2019s meandering path snapped into a clear, focused direction.\n\n4.\nEarly in his career, he sat across from a teenage girl in the Mission who hadn't spoken for weeks. He simply gave her charcoal and paper. For an hour, she drew a frantic, tangled storm of black lines with one tiny, fragile bird taking flight from the corner. She slid the paper across the table, met his eyes, and gave a single, exhausted nod. For Ethan, that drawing was a shout, a confession, a prayer. It was the an undeniable affirmation of his life's work.\n\n5.\nMonths after his decade-long relationship ended at 45, he was making dinner alone in his Inner Sunset apartment. The silence, which had once felt like a crushing weight, was suddenly just\u2026 quiet. He looked at his books, his canvases, the city lights filtering through the window, and felt a surprising sense of peace. It wasn't loneliness, but a comfortable solitude. This subtle shift reshaped his understanding of companionship, revealing the deep value of his own quiet company and the strength found within it."
